AIM

To write a C++ program using the SFML library to create a window and display a simple 2D graph (a line graph) using graphical primitives.

ALGORITHM
1.Start the program.
2.Include SFML headers for graphics and window handling.
3.Create an SFML window with a fixed width and height.
4.Define a set of data points representing a small graph.
5.Convert these data points into sf::VertexArray with LinesStrip type.
6.Enter a window loop that:
7.Checks for window close events
8.Clears the screen
9.Draws the graph
10.Displays the updated window
11.End.

CODE

(Requires SFML installed)

#include <SFML/Graphics.hpp>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    // Create window
    sf::RenderWindow window(sf::VideoMode(800, 600), "SFML Graph Example");

    // Sample data points for graph
    std::vector<float> data = {10, 50, 30, 80, 60, 90, 40};

    // Create vertex array for line graph
    sf::VertexArray graph(sf::LineStrip, data.size());

    // Map data points to screen coordinates
    for (size_t i = 0; i < data.size(); i++) {
        float x = 50 + i * 100;       // spacing on x-axis
        float y = 500 - data[i] * 4;  // scale and invert y-axis

        graph[i].position = sf::Vector2f(x, y);
        graph[i].color = sf::Color::Red;
    }

    // Window loop
    while (window.isOpen()) {
        sf::Event event;
        while (window.pollEvent(event)) {
            if (event.type == sf::Event::Closed)
                window.close();
        }

        window.clear(sf::Color::White);

        // Draw graph
        window.draw(graph);

        window.display();
    }

    return 0;
}

OUTPUT:
When the program runs:

A window titled "SFML Graph Example" opens.
A red line graph is drawn inside the window.
The graph shows the plotted data points connected by straight lines.


RESULT

The program successfully demonstrates how to:

Create a window using SFML

Use sf::VertexArray to draw a graph
